Therefore, the equation $f(f(x)) = 2$ has a total of $\boxed{3}$ solutions.

The distance between the midpoint of $\overline{AB}$ and an endpoint of $\overline{AB}$ is equal to half of the length of $\overline{AB}$. By the distance formula,

\begin{align*}
AB &= \sqrt{((t-4)-(-2))^2 + ((-1)-(t+3))^2}\\
&= \sqrt{(t-2)^2+(t+4)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{2t^2 + 4t + 20}
\end{align*}Also, we know that $(AB/2)^2 = t^2/2 \Longrightarrow AB = 2\sqrt{t^2/2} = \sqrt{2t^2}$. Setting these two expressions equal and squaring, we obtain $$AB^2 = 2t^2 = 2t^2 + 4t + 20 \Longrightarrow 4t + 20 = 0.$$Thus, $t = \boxed{-5}$.

Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{3^2-4(7)(k)}}{14}=\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9-28k}}{14}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-3\pm i\sqrt{299}}{14}$, we have \begin{align*} \sqrt{9-28k}&=i\sqrt{299}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 9-28k&=-299
\\\Rightarrow\qquad -28k&=-308
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{11}.
\end{align*}

